00:57.058 --> 01:00.936
My father was diagnosed
manic depressive in 1967.

01:01.103 --> 01:03.939
He'd been going around Cambridge
in a fake beard

01:04.105 --> 01:06.984
calling himself
Jesus John Harvard.

01:07.151 --> 01:08.694
When he got better,

01:08.861 --> 01:10.571
he started working in
public television in Boston.

01:10.738 --> 01:12.281
He met my mother there.

01:12.448 --> 01:14.408
He walked up
and took her picture.

01:15.659 --> 01:17.369
On their first date,

01:17.536 --> 01:19.663
he took her on a driving tour
of New England

01:19.830 --> 01:22.124
and told her all about
his nervous breakdowns.

01:22.291 --> 01:25.336
She didn't care.
She said it was a crazy time.

01:25.503 --> 01:28.130
Half the people they knew
were going bananas.

01:28.297 --> 01:32.968
So they got married and they
had me... and then my sister.

01:33.135 --> 01:36.847
We were happy.
I know there is more to it than that.

01:37.014 --> 01:38.516
There always is.

01:38.682 --> 01:41.268
♪ Amen

01:41.435 --> 01:44.146
♪ Amen. ♪

01:44.313 --> 01:46.899
Daddy!
We have to go to school.

01:47.066 --> 01:48.818
Not today.
We're celebrating!

01:48.984 --> 01:50.820
- Celebrating what?
- I got fired!

01:50.986 --> 01:52.947
What do you mean?
You just got that job!

01:53.114 --> 01:55.199
Darlings, look around you!

01:55.366 --> 01:58.494
We walk out of our house
into this beautiful world!

01:58.661 --> 02:00.621
But what happened
with your job?

02:00.788 --> 02:03.833
Typical workplace politics.
Who knows who pushed who first?

02:03.999 --> 02:07.378
Either way, I got into a scuffle
with my boss. Forget that.

02:07.545 --> 02:10.005
Let's find some mushrooms
and make an omelette for Mommy.

02:10.172 --> 02:13.050
Does Mommy know
you got fired?

02:40.786 --> 02:42.997
It's magical.

02:43.164 --> 02:46.375
Mommy's gonna be so happy
I kept you out of school.

02:46.542 --> 02:48.377
Get in the car, girls.

02:51.630 --> 02:54.758
Maggie! Where are you going?
What are you doing?

02:54.925 --> 02:56.725
- What's with the suitcases?
- Get in the car.

02:56.844 --> 03:00.431
Maggie! I'm not manic. I'm fine.

03:00.598 --> 03:02.433
I just pulled out the canoe.

03:02.600 --> 03:04.393
I thought we could
paddle up to Lincoln Park

03:04.560 --> 03:06.312
and forage for a picnic.

03:06.478 --> 03:08.147
Isn't it too cold
for a picnic?

03:08.314 --> 03:09.356
Maggie!

03:09.523 --> 03:11.025
I am a man!

03:11.192 --> 03:14.361
Men like to live free!

03:14.528 --> 03:18.490
That's what we do, Maggie.
To hunt and mate!

03:18.657 --> 03:21.994
That's what we do!
That's why we have balls!

03:22.161 --> 03:24.205
It's OK. It's OK.

03:25.497 --> 03:26.832
Ah!

03:28.417 --> 03:30.336
It's gonna be OK.

03:45.684 --> 03:47.645
I'm sorry.

03:54.902 --> 03:56.570
He's sitting on the ground

03:56.737 --> 03:58.656
and all he's wearing
is a bathing suit.

03:58.822 --> 04:01.659
Your father's very sick right now.
He's not himself.

04:03.327 --> 04:05.287
He looks freezing.

04:09.583 --> 04:11.502
Girls, look at me.

04:11.669 --> 04:13.963
I don't want you
telling your friends

04:14.129 --> 04:16.214
or your teachers
about any of this.

04:17.298 --> 04:19.635
We know Daddy's a good person,

04:19.802 --> 04:22.554
and we know
that he would never hurt us,

04:22.721 --> 04:25.557
but it's hard
for people to understand that.

04:25.724 --> 04:27.434
And it's very sad.

04:34.358 --> 04:37.611
"Dear Daddy, I took a walk through
the woods today and said goodbye."

04:37.778 --> 04:40.990
"Mommy had to sell
the car, but we got to go to Dairy Queen."

04:41.156 --> 04:44.159
"I hate that we have to
move to an apartment in the city."

04:44.326 --> 04:47.079
"I got a vanilla saucer
dipped in chocolate. It was so good."

04:47.246 --> 04:50.166
"Mommy says Bohemia is
over, which I don't understand,

04:50.332 --> 04:52.501
"but I think it has something
to do with making money."

04:52.668 --> 04:56.171
<i>"Lots of love, Faith Feather Stuart."</i>

04:56.338 --> 04:59.132
<i>"Amelia Lavender Stuart. "</i>

05:14.648 --> 05:17.276
Babies!

05:18.944 --> 05:22.072
- Hi.
- Want to go see Daddy?

05:22.239 --> 05:24.366
Go on. Go see Daddy.

05:26.201 --> 05:29.038
Little.

05:29.204 --> 05:31.790
Big Little.

05:31.957 --> 05:34.335
- And I'm feeling much better.
- You are?

05:34.501 --> 05:37.588
- Yeah.
- Your stomach is really big.

05:37.755 --> 05:41.967
Oh... That's the medication
they put me on.

05:42.134 --> 05:43.844
It doesn't hurt. Hit it.

05:44.011 --> 05:47.306
Go on. Pound on it.

05:47.473 --> 05:49.016
Jesus!

05:50.100 --> 05:51.935
You gotta be careful.

05:52.102 --> 05:54.813
You never want to do that when
Harry Houdini's not looking,

05:54.980 --> 05:57.274
'cause that's how
they killed him.

05:58.567 --> 06:02.237
- Hi, handsome.
- I got you flowers.

06:02.404 --> 06:07.576
You're so beautiful.
You look like your mommy.

06:07.743 --> 06:09.453
You need help?

06:16.710 --> 06:18.504
How are you feeling?

06:18.670 --> 06:20.214
Mmm...

06:22.091 --> 06:25.636
- I feel great.
- You looked better last week.

06:26.720 --> 06:28.680
Are they adjusting
the medication?

06:28.847 --> 06:31.683
Yeah, they tried
something new on me. It's...

06:31.850 --> 06:33.852
- I want to sit down.
- OK.

06:35.687 --> 06:38.399
I want to be home
with my family.

06:38.565 --> 06:40.317
You will, Daddy.

06:40.484 --> 06:42.444
I love you.

06:42.611 --> 06:45.531
- We love you.
- I love you too, Daddy.

06:45.697 --> 06:47.908
- Love you too.
- Thank you.

06:54.540 --> 06:56.667
The lights on the roof
come in our window at night

06:56.834 --> 06:58.210
and it's too bright.

06:58.377 --> 07:00.087
I can't sleep.
It's bright as day.

07:00.254 --> 07:01.964
- I'll make a curtain.
- They're huge security lights.

07:02.131 --> 07:04.258
- Like you would see at a prison.
- Amelia!

07:04.425 --> 07:06.635
I also wish we could have stayed
out in the country,

07:06.802 --> 07:08.303
but there are
no good jobs in Sudbury.

07:08.470 --> 07:10.013
Your job here isn't good.

07:10.180 --> 07:12.558
I'm gonna find a better one.

07:12.724 --> 07:14.184
Why can't Daddy
live here with us?

07:14.351 --> 07:15.951
I hate visiting him
at the halfway house.

07:16.103 --> 07:17.604
It's almost as bad
as the hospital.

07:17.771 --> 07:19.148
Daddy's still recovering
from his breakdown.

07:19.314 --> 07:20.774
He's a way better cook
than you.

07:28.949 --> 07:30.701
Faith!

07:30.868 --> 07:32.244
What is that?

07:32.411 --> 07:35.122
It's a flower. It's pretty.

07:53.182 --> 07:57.394
♪ Police officer,
how can it be?

07:57.561 --> 08:01.899
♪ You can arrest everybody
but cruel Stack O'Lee

08:02.065 --> 08:06.570
♪ That bad man
Oh, cruel Stack O'Lee... ♪

08:20.417 --> 08:23.003
My father lives here.

08:26.924 --> 08:28.675
How did you know
how to get here?

08:28.842 --> 08:30.427
Came all the way
from school?

08:30.594 --> 08:34.097
- So, what's your plan?
- What's my plan?

08:35.224 --> 08:37.100
Mmm...

08:37.267 --> 08:40.270
My plan is...

08:40.437 --> 08:42.438
...to get out of
this halfway house.

08:42.606 --> 08:44.942
- That's... that's number one.
- I like it.

08:45.108 --> 08:48.946
Then I'll get a job
and an apartment.

08:49.112 --> 08:53.575
And then you girls can come visit me
and have sleepovers

08:53.742 --> 08:58.330
and I'll make crepes
for breakfast and dinner.

08:58.497 --> 09:00.791
And then...

09:00.958 --> 09:07.589
...I'll move back in with you
and Faithie... and Mommy.

09:07.756 --> 09:10.509
That is, if Mommy will have me.

09:13.679 --> 09:16.181
I feel like Lucy
visiting Mr Tumnus.

09:16.348 --> 09:19.226
Oh! That's the nicest thing
anyone's ever said to me.

09:19.393 --> 09:21.436
Mommy says you have
a drinking problem.

09:24.064 --> 09:27.526
I think if you could stop drinking
and take your lithium,

09:27.693 --> 09:29.236
then Mommy
would let you come home.

09:29.403 --> 09:32.072
Do you actually think
Mommy should be

09:32.239 --> 09:33.657
confiding in you this way?

09:33.824 --> 09:36.326
Yes.

09:36.493 --> 09:39.997
Could we please go back to
being Lucy and Mr Tumnus?

09:45.085 --> 09:46.503
- These too.
- OK.

09:49.172 --> 09:50.966
Keller Brothers.

09:52.676 --> 09:54.678
Hey. It's for you.
No personal calls.

09:54.845 --> 09:56.638
- Oh, I'm sorry.
- This is a job!

09:56.805 --> 09:59.308
OK. OK. I'm sorry about that.

09:59.474 --> 10:01.435
Sorry. Sorry.

10:01.602 --> 10:03.604
- Hello?
- It's me.

10:03.770 --> 10:06.148
Amelia came to see me
at the halfway house today.

10:06.315 --> 10:09.735
Everything's fine.
I'm taking her home to your apartment.

10:14.114 --> 10:15.866
- How did she get there?
- Walked.

10:16.033 --> 10:18.076
All the way from school?

10:20.203 --> 10:22.080
I know - I think
we should try and find

10:22.247 --> 10:24.166
a therapist
for her to talk to.

10:30.297 --> 10:31.840
She's gotten so good.

10:32.007 --> 10:34.676
- That's fantastic!
- That's great, sweetpea.

10:37.596 --> 10:39.139
How's the job?

10:39.306 --> 10:41.224
Oh, the job.

10:41.391 --> 10:43.894
I can't believe
I'm doing this.

10:47.689 --> 10:49.900
- Oh.
- Oh!

10:51.318 --> 10:53.362
- Forgot the laundry.
- We'll get it!

10:54.863 --> 10:56.531
Faithie!

11:06.375 --> 11:09.336
And creamy spinach.
I just love spinach.

11:09.503 --> 11:11.922
Creamy little things are good.

11:12.089 --> 11:14.549
- Hi.
- Hi.

11:14.716 --> 11:17.052
You guys go to Lincoln?

11:17.219 --> 11:18.762
No. We go to Peabody.

11:18.929 --> 11:20.889
Peabody's the best public school
in our city.

11:21.056 --> 11:24.267
We are not
in the Peabody School district.

11:24.434 --> 11:26.434
If you live here,
you're supposed to go to Lincoln,

11:26.561 --> 11:30.190
a school that is totally, 100% terrible.

11:30.357 --> 11:33.360
Unless you like getting
your 'A' kicked by Irish kids.

11:33.527 --> 11:35.612
I don't want to
get my 'A' kicked.

11:35.779 --> 11:38.407
- Honey, nobody does.
- Well, we go to Peabody.

11:38.573 --> 11:40.992
You don't get it.
What you're doing is illegal.

11:41.159 --> 11:43.370
And it's not fair.
It's not at all fair.

11:43.537 --> 11:47.374
- You guys are gonna go to jail.
- 'Bye!

11:47.541 --> 11:50.293
What if somebody asks me
where I live? I don't want to lie.

11:50.460 --> 11:52.546
Amelia, Peabody's the best
public school in the city.

11:52.713 --> 11:54.840
I don't care.
I don't want to lie.

11:55.006 --> 11:56.726
You're not lying, sweetheart.
Mommy's lying.

11:56.883 --> 11:59.720
I don't want to go to Lincoln!
They said we'll get beat up.

11:59.886 --> 12:02.222
Don't worry about that.
I'm gonna teach you how to fight.

12:02.389 --> 12:04.015
What if my teacher finds out
I'm lying?

12:04.182 --> 12:06.643
Miss Hendricks loves you.
You're her best student.

12:06.810 --> 12:09.354
They said we're gonna get
our 'A' kicked by Irish kids!

12:09.521 --> 12:10.897
- You're not gonna get...
- Who said that?

12:11.064 --> 12:12.566
You'll be kicking 'A'!

12:12.733 --> 12:15.193
If you wanted us to go to
the Peabody School so bad,

12:15.360 --> 12:17.696
why didn't we move into
the Peabody School district?

12:17.863 --> 12:19.865
Amelia, because
we cannot afford it.

12:20.031 --> 12:22.075
We are lucky we got
a rent-controlled apartment.

12:22.242 --> 12:25.829
- But Daddy's family is so rich!
- Yes, but we have no money!

12:25.996 --> 12:29.249
I send my résumé out every day
and I get nothing.

12:29.416 --> 12:31.710
I've just spent my last $12.

12:31.877 --> 12:34.755
You girls want to be poor
and have a bad education?

12:36.840 --> 12:39.009
Seconds, anyone?

12:42.846 --> 12:45.223
Thank you, Cam,
for this delicious dinner.

12:45.390 --> 12:47.642
It could be like this
every night.

12:47.809 --> 12:50.395
Yes, that would be nice,
but I need a husband, not a wife.

12:50.562 --> 12:53.523
I would like to be a husband,
but my wife won't let me.

12:53.690 --> 12:55.400
Your wife would let you
be a husband

12:55.567 --> 12:58.028
if you made it possible for her
to just be your wife.

12:58.195 --> 13:00.363
He wants her to be a wife,
but she insists

13:00.530 --> 13:03.033
on being a husband
who makes me be his wife.

13:52.290 --> 13:54.918
What did he say?

13:55.085 --> 13:58.630
He said that we don't live
in the Peabody School district

13:58.797 --> 14:01.591
and that you and Faith
have to go to Lincoln.

14:01.758 --> 14:05.470
- I'm so sorry, Mommy.
- Honey, don't.

14:05.637 --> 14:09.516
Please don't cry, Amelia.
Don't apologise to me.

14:09.683 --> 14:12.185
He asked where we lived
and I didn't know what to say.

14:12.352 --> 14:14.938
I know. I know.
You did the right thing.

14:15.105 --> 14:17.023
I never wanted you to lie.

14:17.190 --> 14:19.693
He said it was illegal
what we were doing.

14:19.860 --> 14:22.696
I know. I just...

14:24.447 --> 14:27.117
I guess I...
I wasn't thinking, honey.

14:27.284 --> 14:29.619
I wanted you and Faith
to go to the best school.

14:29.786 --> 14:33.665
What if Faithie gets beat up
and it's all because of me?

14:33.832 --> 14:36.751
Faith is not gonna get beat up.

14:36.918 --> 14:38.461
She bites.

14:39.713 --> 14:43.633
Sleeping bags, pyjamas,
stuffed animals, books,

14:43.800 --> 14:45.468
changes of clothes -
what am I forgetting?

14:45.635 --> 14:48.555
- Toothbrushes.
- I bought toothbrushes.

14:48.722 --> 14:50.042
They can keep 'em
at my apartment.

14:50.181 --> 14:52.225
And I found
these two cardboard boxes.

14:52.392 --> 14:54.185
I set 'em up like beds.
They're gonna flip.

14:54.352 --> 14:56.021
They're so excited.

14:56.187 --> 14:57.827
- Do you want some tea?
- Yes, please. Oh.

14:57.898 --> 14:59.818
During the day, they can
turn them on their sides

14:59.900 --> 15:01.276
and they become puppet theatres.

15:01.443 --> 15:03.612
You're going to have
so much fun.

15:03.778 --> 15:07.073
- Do you want some toast?
- Please.

15:10.619 --> 15:12.579
Now that I got my own place,
Maggie, I mean,

15:12.746 --> 15:15.665
I'm happy to stop by
and pick up the kids any time,

15:15.832 --> 15:17.459
have 'em stay over.

15:17.626 --> 15:19.753
- Thank you.
- There's room for you too.

15:21.087 --> 15:22.672
Just kidding.

15:22.839 --> 15:24.799
Not until you're ready.

15:24.966 --> 15:27.052
- Oh, it's good tea. Cam?
- Mmm?

15:27.218 --> 15:30.764
Um...
I got into business school.

15:32.223 --> 15:35.101
Maggie Stuart,
you are some punkins!

15:36.853 --> 15:40.273
I wish I had some of that
bourgeois Midwestern can-do.

15:42.525 --> 15:45.195
A scholarship... to Columbia.

15:46.363 --> 15:48.198
Wait. You can't take the girls
to New York.

15:48.365 --> 15:50.241
No, of course not-
I can't even afford

15:50.408 --> 15:52.452
my own studio apartment
in New York.

15:52.619 --> 15:55.038
So, what about the girls?

15:56.915 --> 15:59.459
OK. Here's my proposal.

16:00.627 --> 16:04.047
I can get my degree in 18 months
if I do a summer session.

16:04.214 --> 16:06.341
And Jenny's mom can rent me

16:06.508 --> 16:07.926
a very small room
in her apartment.

16:08.093 --> 16:10.387
So I go to New York.

16:10.553 --> 16:15.183
You move in here with the girls
and you take care of them.

16:17.602 --> 16:19.688
- Me?
- Yes, you.

16:19.854 --> 16:22.649
You miss them.
And they miss you so much, Cam.

16:22.816 --> 16:27.988
I can get my MBA in 18 months,
and then I come back to Boston,

16:28.154 --> 16:31.074
I get a job and I move back in.

16:31.241 --> 16:34.494
But... but... but... I mean, yes.

16:34.661 --> 16:36.496
Yes.

16:38.248 --> 16:40.458
- I know it is a lot.
- No, no, no, no, no.

16:40.625 --> 16:42.544
- But... but...
- Uh... uh... uh...

16:42.711 --> 16:45.046
You know, the doctor even said
that I would be...

16:45.213 --> 16:47.653
I suppose it'd be good for me
to have... to have some purpose.

16:47.757 --> 16:50.010
A routine.
That's what the doctor said.

16:50.176 --> 16:52.721
- That's exactly what you need.
- Yes, yes, a routine.

16:52.887 --> 16:54.889
- Putting food on the table.
- Yes.

16:55.056 --> 16:57.726
Taking them to school
every... morning.

16:57.892 --> 16:59.853
Putting them to bed
every night.

17:00.020 --> 17:02.355
Making sure they brush
their teeth and their hair

17:02.522 --> 17:03.940
twice a day.

17:04.107 --> 17:05.483
The laundry.

17:05.650 --> 17:08.444
My God, that sounds like a lot.

17:08.611 --> 17:10.989
Cam, it is a lot.

17:11.156 --> 17:14.451
But we are sinking
deeper and deeper into a hole.

17:14.617 --> 17:16.911
Cam, I have to do something.

17:17.078 --> 17:19.414
- Do you understand?
- Oh, Maggie, you're right.

17:19.580 --> 17:21.750
I mean,
that new school of theirs

17:21.915 --> 17:23.835
certainly feels like
a bit of a reformatory.

17:24.002 --> 17:27.088
It's grim. And you and I
went to good schools.

17:27.255 --> 17:29.883
- We had piano lessons.
- I never had any lessons.

17:30.050 --> 17:33.136
But you learned to fence
and you learned to ski and play chess...

17:33.303 --> 17:35.584
But I never had lessons.
My family taught me those things.

17:35.680 --> 17:38.183
The point is, Cameron,
you and I,

17:38.349 --> 17:41.811
we had the best education,
and I want that for our children.

17:41.978 --> 17:45.148
I do too, but 18 months,
that's a lot of routine.

17:45.315 --> 17:49.569
You can do it. And I'll come
every weekend to help you.

17:49.736 --> 17:52.072
- Every weekend?
- Every weekend.

17:52.238 --> 17:55.116
- And you'll stay here with us?
- Of course. Yes.

17:55.283 --> 17:56.951
So we'll be
like a family again?

18:00.622 --> 18:02.415
Yes.

18:05.168 --> 18:08.296
I'm afraid we need to intervene
on our son's behalf and say no.

18:08.463 --> 18:10.757
- He's not up to the task.
- I know he can do it.

18:10.924 --> 18:13.343
The doctor says I need
more responsibilities, not less.

18:13.510 --> 18:15.762
You're a man. Even if you could,
why would you want to?

18:15.929 --> 18:18.264
We just don't want you
to tax yourself, darling boy.

18:18.431 --> 18:20.183
We met with Dr Wendell.

18:20.350 --> 18:22.631
He says Cam made an excellent
recovery from his breakdown,

18:22.769 --> 18:24.771
and he thinks
that he can do it.

18:24.938 --> 18:27.440
Is this something to do
with feminism?

18:27.607 --> 18:30.360
We're living
at the poverty level.

18:30.527 --> 18:32.278
The girls are going
to a terrible school.

18:32.445 --> 18:33.925
Our children went
to the best schools.

18:34.030 --> 18:35.406
It didn't add up to much.

18:35.573 --> 18:37.408
Our children are delightful!

18:37.575 --> 18:39.702
Absolutely, but not one of them
is self-supporting.

18:39.869 --> 18:42.038
Well, Murray, lest you forget,
neither are we.

18:42.205 --> 18:43.623
I think it's admirable
what Maggie's doing.

18:43.790 --> 18:45.458
I agree.
Very commendable.

18:45.625 --> 18:48.419
Don't we have some silver
